# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: battle-of-navarino
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] The **1st Regiment Greek Light Infantry** (1810–12) was a light infantry regiment, founded as a *local establishment* in British service consisting mostly of Greek and Albanian enlisted men and Greek and British officers that served during the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Later it became a regular British Army regiment as the **1st Greek Light Infantry ("The Duke of York's")** (1812–16).
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] It had no official association with the modern state of Greece or the Filiki Eteria or any Greek War of Independence groups; however, several future leaders of the War of Independence fought in its ranks, as did a number of rank-and-file klephts and armatoloi.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] The British Army during the Napoleonic Wars was small (~40,000 troops) at the outset compared to those of other European countries like France and Prussia.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] The British Army used foreign volunteers, such as French Royalists, Germans, Greeks and Corsicans to supplement its forces.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] In 1813 one fifth of the army, 52,000 men, were such volunteers.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] The British Army in 1813 contained over 250,000 men.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Meanwhile, the Ottoman Empire, which ruled the majority of Greek-speaking areas at the time, participated in on-again, off-again alliances with France under Napoleon.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Many Greeks fleeing Ottoman persecution or local disputes on the mainland ended up in the Ionian Islands, which were beyond the reach of Ottoman authorities.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] When Britain took over the Ionian Islands, it initially relied on small numbers of British and British-foreign troops along with the local volunteer militias, the largest of which was on Zakynthos (*Zante*), numbering some 2,000 men, with another approximately 2,000 dispersed over the other islands.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] These were armed at their own expense, and unpaid.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] They were drawn from the population of the islands and from mainland Greece and Albania, from men with varying levels of experience.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] A decision was taken to form an elite, paid unit from among the experienced troops, and to give them additional training.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] The regiment was raised in the Ionian Islands in March 1810 by then-Captain Richard Church who already had experience managing foreign (i.e. non-British) troops from his previous appointment in the Royal Corsican Rangers.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Later, it was moved to Zante (Zakynthos) which served as its base and reached its full authorized strength.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] In 1811, Church was promoted major, and Brigadier General Robert Oswald, late of the 35th Foot as colonel for the *Greek Light Infantry Corps*, which at that time consisted of only the nominal battalion-sized 1st Regiment.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Recruitment began for the second regiment, in order to build up to the corps-level strength, after which Oswald was promoted brigadier for the corps.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] The regiment was put on British establishment in 1812, becoming an official regiment of the British Army, and increased to an authorized strength of 1,129 men of all ranks.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] It was sent to suppress an insurrection in Montenegro in June of that year, but baulked at being sent to Sicily in 1813.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] On 22 May 1813 the unit was reviewed and found to be in a "very indifferent state, with no field officer present and company officers at a loss to discipline the men"; Church was badly wounded in the arm in the attack on Lefkada and did not return to the regiment after recuperating.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Instead, he was promoted lieutenant colonel went on to become colonel commandant the 2nd Greek Light Infantry, and his second-in-command went with him.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] At least one replacement major was cashiered for an unspecified offence, and another transferred out.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Henry Cuyler of the 85th Foot as colonel commandant of the regiment on February 2, 1813.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] A 250-man detachment took part in the British Siege of Genoa and La Spezia in the spring of 1814.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Officers were Greek, apart from British regimental staff.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] The day-to-day language of the regiment was Greek; however, in order to avoid confusion when the regiment or elements of the regiment were brigaded with other British units, English was used for all drill commands.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] This was generally the practice in all foreign units recruited by the British at the time.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Elements of the regiment were often brigaded with other units, for instance, the assaults on Santa Maura, Genoa and La Spezzia also included elements of the Calabrian Free Corps.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] The men of the regiment were reported as wearing "Albanian dress" in 1810; their orders stated "clothing and accoutrements were to be made in the Albanian fashion".
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Enlisted men wore red jackets with yellow cuffs, facings, and trim; for the officers, these were gold and white, over a white shirt, *foustanella*, breeches and stockings.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Headwear was usually a red cap (resembling a fez or small beret, like the *fario* of the Greek Evzones).
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] In some contemporary prints, the officers and men are depicted wearing fillets (*kefalodesmoi*) instead of caps.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Officers wore a crested red dragoon-style helmet, as depicted in the drawing of Richard Church and of later drawings of Greek War of Independence (after 1821) leader Theodoros Kolokotronis who continued to wear the helmet.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Footwear consisted of what are described as "tied sandals" and in illustrations resemble the moccasin-like *tsarouhia* of the Evzones, only they lack pompoms and have extra lacing to keep them secure.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Officers are depicted as wearing taller, higher-heeled three-quarter shoes or short boots.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] The troops refused to carry British knapsacks, only haversacks.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] The regiment's soldiers were armed initially with sawed-off muskets, but gradually came to prefer British-issue muskets and by 1813 this is what they carried.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] They wore sword bayonets on waist belts instead of shoulder or cross-belts (this was also common among British light infantry and rifle units).
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Officers carried longer sabre-style weapons, just as their light infantry counterparts in Western European armies did.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] The men were supposed to be issued pistols, but it was "thought prudent" not to issue them to the men as they were, in the view of one historian 'always volatile', although officers carried.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] An 1812 print by Charles Hamilton Smith shows enlisted men of the 2nd Regiment Greek Light Infantry wearing pistols, another two by Goddard depict an enlisted man with a single pistol, possibly French pattern, and the other an officer of the 1st with a brace of pistols and enlisted man with one.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Kolokotronis sported a brace of engraved pistols and an ornate cavalry-style cuirass, which are now on display at the National Historical Museum, Athens.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Richard Church was depicted wearing a similar helmet-and-cuirass outfit plus metal greaves and knee protectors with gilt lion's heads along with a braided version of the uniform of the 2nd Regiment Greek Light Infantry, in a painting now housed in the Royal Gallery.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] Both of these romanticized outfits imitating Ancient Greek styles were probably intended for ceremony and were not worn in their entirety in combat, although Kolokotronis did sometimes wear the helmet when he fought, even after the regiment disbanded.
[src:battle-of-navarino/1st-regiment-greek-light-infantry] As officers, they both would have had the privilege of wearing pistols, and in Kolokotronis' career as a klepht, the carrying of more than one pistol would not have been uncommon.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-doukas] Doukas was born in 1790 in Permet, then Ottoman Empire, now in southern Albania.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-doukas] He then moved to Ioannina where he attended the local Maroutsaia School.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-doukas] At the time of the outbreak of the Greek War of Independence (1821) he lived in Livadeia in Central Greece.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-doukas] He became one of the most important political leaders of the Greek Revolution in Eastern Central Greece and Euboea.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-doukas] Doukas was politically attached to Ioannis Kolettis and his French Party.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-doukas] Doukas was also in close contact with the most important local military figures of the War of Independence.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-doukas] He participated in the First National Assembly at Epidaurus (1821–1822) as a representative of Thebes, as well as in the Fourth National Assembly at Argos.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-doukas] In 1825 he became Minister of War in the revolutionary government of Greece.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-doukas] He latter participated in the liberation of Euboea by the Greek forces and was in charge of the surrender committee of the Ottoman garrison in Karystos, southern Euboea, in April 1833.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-doukas] After the end of the successful national struggle Doukas became member of various state cabinets from 1850 to 1860, during the reign of King Otto.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] After the Napoleonic Wars, where he served as an officer, Friedel travelled with a noble compatriot of his to the Ottoman Empire.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] He was initiated into the Filiki Eteria (Greek Society of Friends) and after numerous expeditions and missions in Russian territories, he ended up in Zakynthos.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] He witnessed the beginning of the Greek War of Independence in Peloponnese, where he enlisted in the army as a volunteer claiming to be Baron Friedel von Friedelsburg, a second lieutenant of aristocratic origin.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] Friedel met many fighters of the Greek War of Independence in person such as Theodoros Kolokotronis, Nikitaras, Petrobey Mavromichalis, Markos Botsaris, Demetrios Ypsilantis, Ioannis Kolettis, Alexandros Mavrokordatos, etc.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] He also gained the trust of Demetrios Ypsilantis with his cultivation and proficiency in Greek and was thus assigned a multitude of missions.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] In June 1822, though, a compatriot of his who was a Danish sub-lieutenant unveiled his lies.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] Friedel was then discharged from the Greek army and in 1823 he travelled to Egypt in order to gather funds from his expatriates for the Greek War of Independence.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] 1824 found him in Messolonghi with Lord Byron.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] Meyer published an article in the Greek newspaper Ellinika Chronika in which he warned philhellenic companies to avoid the fraudulent Friedel, he fled to London where he opened a lithographer’s shop.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] Once his hopes of a military career evaporated, Friedel showed his talent at painting.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] The 24 real-life portraits of the leaders of the Greek War of Independence which he created, were lithographically printed and colorized by J.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] These portraits circulated in Paris and London between 1825 and 1826 thus aiding the philhellenic committees in their effort to raise awareness in Europe of the Greek War of Independence.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] Because of health complications, Friedel was forced to leave England and head to southern France and then Italy before finally returning to Athens in 1849 where he was awarded two important decorations for his contribution to the Greek Struggle for Independence.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] He then travelled to Smyrna, where he taught at a Greek school for two years.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] Friedel stayed in the capital of the Ottoman Empire during the Crimean War where he painted the portraits of several politicians.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] For reasons relating to his therapy again, he stayed in Bohemia until 1861 before heading back to Athens.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] He left again in 1863 and after a short stay in Istanbul, he returned yet again to Athens in 1865.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adam-friedel] There, he submitted a report to King George consisting of supporting documents, claims and information about his life and his contributions to the cause of Greece’s Independence, asking for a pension for his services to the country.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] His father Ioannis, of Chian descent, was *demogérontas* in Smyrna, a seat similar to the prokritoi of mainland Greece, but elected by the Greek community of the town and not imposed by the Ottomans.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] He was exceptionally passionate about philosophy, literacy and linguistics and studied greatly throughout his youth.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] He initially studied in his hometown, Smyrna, where he graduated from the Evangelical Greek School.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] After his school years, he lived in Amsterdam for a while as a merchant, but soon decided that he wanted to study in a university.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] He also studied Hebrew, Dutch, French and English apart from his knowledge of ancient Greek and Latin.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Korais studied at the school of medicine of the University of Montpellier from 1782 to 1787.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] His 1786 diploma thesis was entitled *Pyretologiae Synopsis*, while his 1787 doctoral thesis was entitled *Medicus Hippocraticus*.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] He traveled to Paris where he would continue his enthusiasm for knowledge.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] There he decided to translate ancient Greek authors and produced thirty volumes of those translations, being one of the first modern Greek philologists and publishers of ancient Greek literature.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] After 1788 he was to spend most of his life as an expatriate in Paris.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] As classical scholar, Korais was repelled by the Byzantine influence on Greek society and was a fierce critic of the lack of education amongst the clergy and their subservience to the Ottoman Empire, although he conceded it was the Orthodox Church that preserved the national identity of Greeks.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Korais believed Western Europe was the heir of the ancient Greek civilization, which had to be transmitted to the modern Greeks through education.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Additionally, he advocated the restoration and use of the term "Hellene" (Έλληνας) or "Graikos" (Γραικός) as an ethnonym for the Greeks, in the place of *Romiós*, that was seen negatively by him.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] While in Paris, he was witness to the French Revolution.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] He was influenced by the revolutionary and liberal sentiments of his age.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] He admired Thomas Jefferson and exchanged political and philosophical thoughts with the American statesman.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] A typical man of the Enlightenment, Korais encouraged wealthy Greeks to open new libraries and schools throughout Greece.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Korais believed that education would ensure not only the achievement of independence but also the establishment of a proper constitution for the newly liberated Greek state.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] He envisioned a democratic Greece, recapturing the glory of the Golden Age of Pericles.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Korais died in Paris aged 84 soon after publishing the first volume of his autobiography.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] In 1877, his remains were transferred to Greece to be buried there.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Korais's most lasting contributions were literary.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Those who were instrumental in publishing, and presenting his work to the public were merchants from Chios.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] He felt eternally grateful to these merchants, since without them, it would have been financially impossible for him to publish his works.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] These works included an edition of Strabo in Greek, another on Marcus Aurelius, his translation of Herodotus, the translation of the *Iliad*, and his main literary work, the seventeen volumes of the "Library of Greek Literature".
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] His political writing begins with the publication at the opening of the nineteenth century of *Asma Polemistirion* ("War Chant") and *Salpisma Polemistirion* ("Military Bugal Call"), celebrating the presence of Greek troops fighting alongside the French in Egypt.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Earlier he had confronted with his *Adelphiki Didaskalia* the Orthodox Patriarch of Jerusalem for urging the Sultan's Christian subjects (with the religious brochure *Patriki Didaskalia*) to support the Ottomans in the war against the "atheistic" French.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] On contrary, he made a call to the Greeks to fight beside the French, "who have the military virtue of the ancient Greeks", against the Ottoman tyranny.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] In 1803, Korais went on to publish his *Report on the Present State of Civilization in Greece*, based on a series of lectures he had given in Paris, extolling the link between the rise of a new Greek mercantile class and the advance of the Modern Greek Enlightenment.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] In *What should we Greeks do in the Present Circumstances?*, a work of 1805, he tried to win his compatriots over to Napoleon and away from the cause of their Russian co-religionists.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Away from contemporary politics, Korais did much to revive the idea of Greece with the creation of the Hellenic Library, devoted to new editions of some of the classical texts, starting with Homer in 1805.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Over the following twenty years many others appeared, with lengthy prefaces by Korais entitled 'Impromptu Reflections', with his views on political, educational and linguistic matters.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Although the broad mass of the Greek people was beyond his reach, he played an important part in the shaping of a new consciousness among the intelligentsia, which was to play a part in the creation of a new national movement.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] With the breakout of the Greek Revolution in 1821, he was too old to join the struggle.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] However his house in Paris became a centre for informations, meetings among the Parisian Greeks and financial aid.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] He wrote also many letters advising the revolutionaries.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Initially a supporter of Kapodistrias, finally he opposed his policies.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Korais was Greek Orthodox but also a critic of many practices of the Orthodox church.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] He was a fierce critic of the Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople, considering it a useful tool in the hands of the Ottomans against Greek independence.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] So, later, he was one of the supporters of the newly established Church of Greece.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] He was also critic of monasticism, the lack of education in the clergy, and practices like that of the "Holy Fire".
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] He was a supporter of religious freedom, empiricism, rationalism and tolerance.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] He set himself in opposition to some metaphysical ideals of Greek custom and sought to mould Greek Orthodoxy towards a more syncretic religious basis, in order to bring it under the auspices of liberal thought and government.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] One of his most significant accomplishments was his contribution to the standardisation of the modern Greek language.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] During his lifetime, the Greeks were widely dispersed around the Mediterranean and throughout Europe, and the language they spoke contained many foreign elements, depending on the region and local traditions.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Korais proposed a standard language purged of many such foreign elements (especially Turkish, but also Western words and phrases).
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Moreover, there was a variety of idioms spoken by Greeks in everyday life and no common agreement on which dialect should serve as the basis for Standard Modern Greek.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Finally, people involved in the Greek language question were also divided between "archaists" and proponents of a simpler standard language.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Korais's solution was to take a middle path regarding all these issues.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] He cleansed his proposed standard language from elements that he considered too foreign or too vulgar.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Moreover, he proposed the creation of a "katharevousa" (a "purified" version of modern Greek), based on the ecclesiastical language used by the Greek Orthodox Church, close to Koine Greek.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] This standard was eventually adopted by scholars and the Greek state.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] This element holds significant importance if one takes into consideration the fact that these post-Revolution Constitutions still, to the present day, form the basis of the Greek Constitution and the philosophy on which the guiding principles of the Greek legal and judicial system are rooted in.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] The influence Korais exercised on Greek Law was due to a personal relationship the intellectual formed with another Greek intellectual, the legal scholar of international repute N.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Saripolos, who, after the Greek Revolution, became the founding father of Greek Law and the "author" of the Greek Constitution.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Proof of this relationship and of the strong and progressive views Korais held on how the legal system of the new Greek state should be formed, is based on correspondence exchanged between the two men, during a long period of time, beginning before the Greek Revolution.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Korais was declared *Pater Patriae* ("Pateras tis Patridos") by the revolutionaries at the Third National Assembly at Troezen.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Korais' portrait was depicted on the reverse of the Greek ₯100 banknote of 1978–2001.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] Many streets all over Greece are named after him, while his archive can be found in Korais Library in Chios (town).
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] "Adamantios Korais" is also the name of the ferry connecting Alexandroupoli, Samothrace, and Lemnos.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adamantios-korais] The vessel, built in 1987 in Onomichi Japan, was previously operated by Zante Ferries and is now operated by Fast Ferries.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] The **Adana campaign** occurred after Ottoman forces seized the city of Adana from the Mamluk Sultanate.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] The Mamluks responded by sending a force under Commander and Chief Uzbek, and besieged Adana.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] The Ottomans responded by sending a large relief force that was defeated.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] The Ottoman Empire had launched a campaign in 1485 against the Mamluk holdings in Southern Turkey and in Cicilia Armenia, seizing areas such as Adana.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] The Mamluk Forces in the Taurus Mountains withdrew to Aleppo.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] In order to respond, Sultan Qaitbey had Atabeg Uzbek launch a counter offensive.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] To this cause Qaitbey had granted Uzbek 3,000 Royal Mamluks as well as Nine of the 15 Emirs of 1,000.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] The force set off from Cairo over Damascus to Aleppo, recruiting local Syrian peasants along the way.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] In February the Mamluks arrived at Adana.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] After a peace message by Uzbek was ignored, the Mamluks confronted an Ottoman force outside the city.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] The Ottomans were quickly routed, with many fleeing.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] Around 800 were captured, including 17 commanders and paraded in Damascus, Aleppo, and Cairo.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] After the battle, the Mamluks besieged Adana.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] When Sultan Bayezid II learned of the offensive on Adana, he sent Hersek-oglu to lead an Ottoman army to relieve Adana.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] Hersek-oglu was the son of Stjepan Vukčić, Duke of Herzegovina, who was sent as a hostage to the court of Mehmed II.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] When Bayezid seized power, he allowed Kersek-oglu to marry one of his daughters, and also granted him a high position.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] When Hersek-oglu's approached the Mamluk Army, his reconnaissance unit was routed by the Mamluks.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] The survivors managed to report that the Mamluks had less than 15,000 soldiers.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] There, Hersek-oglu's forces suffered a massive defeat.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] The Turkmen contingents fled during the beginning of the battle.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] Hersek-oglu and 200 of his Janissaries fought on, despite being encircled.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] He was wounded and captured by the Mamluks.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] Among the captives were also the son of the late vezir Mustafa Pasha, Kiral-oglu, (son of Isfendiyar-oğlu) Kızıl Ahmed, (Sanjakbegi of Kengırı) Ahmed Beg, and the sultan's chief pantry-keeper (kilerjibaşı) Süleyman Aga.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] After the battle, the Adana garrison of 1,500 fighters also surrendered.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] The Ottoman prisoners were sent to Syria.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] The Mamluk victory allowed the Mamluks to re-establish control of Tartus and Adana.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adana-campaign] Despite attempts to broker peace by the Mamluks, the Ottomans would continue to launch further offensives which would eventually lead to the Ottoman conquest of Cilicia.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The **Adriatic campaign of 1807–1814** was a minor theatre of war of the Napoleonic Wars in which the Royal Navy, assisted by Austrian, Montenegrin and Greek troops, attacked the combined forces of the First French Empire, Kingdom of Italy and Kingdom of Naples in the Adriatic Sea from 1807 to 1814.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Much of the region was under direct or indirect French control, coming under France's domination as a result of Treaty of Pressburg which brought an end to the War of the Third Coalition.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Control of the Adriatic brought numerous advantages to the French Navy, allowing rapid transit of troops from Italy to the Balkans and Austria for campaigning in the east and giving France possession of numerous shipbuilding facilities, particularly the large naval yards of Venice.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] From 1807, when the Treaty of Tilsit precipitated a Russian withdrawal from the Septinsular Republic, the French Navy held naval supremacy in the region.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The Treaty of Tilsit also contained a secret clause that guaranteed French assistance in any war fought between the Russians and the Ottoman Empire.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] To fulfil this clause, Napoleon would have to secure his supply lines to the east by developing the French armies in Illyria.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] This required control of the Adriatic against increasingly aggressive British raiders.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The Royal Navy decided to prevent these troop convoys from reaching Illyria and sought to break French hegemony in the region, resulting in a six-year naval campaign.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The campaign was not uniform in approach; British and French forces were limited by the dictates of the wider Mediterranean and global conflict, and consequently ship numbers fluctuated.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Although numerous commanders held commands in the region, the two most important personalities were those of William Hoste and Bernard Dubourdieu, whose exploits were celebrated in their respective national newspapers during 1810 and 1811.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The campaign between the two officers reached a climax at the Battle of Lissa in March 1811, when Dubourdieu was killed and his squadron defeated by Hoste in a celebrated action.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The events of 1811 gave the British dominance in the Adriatic for the remainder of the war.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] British and Greek expeditionary forces steadily captured fortified French islands and their raiding parties inflicted havoc on trade across the region.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] As a result, French plans against the Ottoman Empire were cancelled, La Grande Armée turning towards Russia.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] British forces continued operations until the advancing armies of the Sixth Coalition drove the French from the shores of the Adriatic in early 1814, British troops and marines assisting in the capture of several important French cities, including Fiume (Rijeka) and Trieste.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] There had been a French presence in the Adriatic Sea since the Treaty of Campo Formio during the French Revolutionary War.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Campo Formio marked the end of the War of the First Coalition in 1797 and confirmed the demise of the independent Republic of Venice and the division of its territory between the French Republic and the Austrian Empire.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] One of France's gains from this division were the seven Ionian Islands that controlled the entrance to the Adriatic.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] These French outposts in the Eastern Mediterranean were considered a threat by both the Russian and the Ottoman Empires and in 1798 a united Russo-Ottoman force attacked the massively fortified French citadel on Corfu, which fell the following year after a four-month siege.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The victors took possession of the islands and from them created the Septinsular Republic, nominally Ottoman, practically independent and guaranteed by the Russian Navy.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] On mainland Europe, the rise of Napoleon Bonaparte as the ruler of the new French Empire resulted in a new conflict, the War of the Third Coalition in 1805, which ended disastrously for the Austrian and Russian allied armies at the Battle of Austerlitz.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The treaties that ended the war created two French client monarchies in Italy, the Kingdom of Italy and the Kingdom of Naples, and French troops were left holding substantial parts of the Eastern coastline of the Adriatic in Dalmatia.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] These holdings significantly increased French naval interest in the Adriatic, which was well supplied with excellent ports and shipbuilding facilities, particularly at Venice.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The Russian garrison on Corfu, augmented with a powerful naval squadron, effectively blocked French use of the Adriatic by sealing the entrance through the Straits of Otranto.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] French military concerns were also directed further north at this time, resulting in the War of the Fourth Coalition during 1806 and 1807 that saw Napoleon's armies overrun Prussia and force the Russians to sign the Treaty of Tilsit on 7 July 1807.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] One of the minor clauses of this treaty transferred the Ionian Islands back into French hands, the Russians withdrawing completely from the Adriatic.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] This withdrawal supported a hidden clause in the treaty that guaranteed French support in the continuing Russian war with the Ottomans in the Balkans.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] As the Russians withdrew, the French immediately despatched garrisons to the Ionian Islands, rapidly amassing over 7,400 French and Neapolitan troops on Corfu alone.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] This effectively turned the Adriatic into a sheltered French sea from which they could be free to despatch raiders against British convoys, colonies and Royal Navy blockade squadrons, which had controlled the Mediterranean since the Battle of Trafalgar two years earlier.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] To facilitate this, the French Navy placed significant orders at the Venetian naval yards, intending to build forces in the region with locally produced and crewed vessels.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The Royal Navy's Mediterranean Fleet responded rapidly to this threat, and in November 1807 the fourth rate ship HMS *Glatton* and several smaller craft were blockading Corfu, seizing several French and Italian reinforcement convoys.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Encouraged by the success of the blockade, small British raiders began entering the Adriatic independently, to prey on French convoys along the Italian coast.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] One of the first British operations in the region was the seizure of the small Dalmatian Island of Lissa, for use as a safe harbour deep in nominally French-controlled waters.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The largely uninhabited island was rapidly developed into an effective naval base with the construction of a town and harbour at Port St.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] During 1807, British ships stationed in the Adriatic were relatively small and their impact was consequently minor.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] British raiders also limited their attacks on the Illyrian coast to purely military objectives in order to maintain the support of the local population, who supplied the British cruisers with food, water and naval stores.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The French Mediterranean Fleet, led by Admiral Ganteaume made a foray to Corfu in February 1808 that the British blockading squadron was powerless to stop, but this was the only attempt by the French to send ships of the line to the region and the fleet had returned to Toulon by mid-March.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The first major British deployment into the Adriatic came in May 1808, when the frigate HMS *Unite* under Captain Patrick Campbell arrived off Venice.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] During May, Campbell severely disrupted French and Italian shipping off the busiest Adriatic seaport and captured three ships sent against him by the Italian Navy.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The French response to these depredations was to despatch the small frigate *Var* to Venice, an action which had little effect on British operations.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] British activity in the Adriatic was however curtailed during the year by the British war with the Ottoman Empire, which absorbed the scant British naval resources in the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The British presence in the Adriatic was greatly strengthened in 1809 with the arrival of the frigates HMS *Amphion* under William Hoste and HMS *Belle Poule* under James Brisbane.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] These reinforcements made an immediate impact with a series of raids in the Dalmatian and Ionian islands.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] In February *Belle Poule* captured the *Var* off Valona; the French responded by despatching the frigates *Danaé* and *Flore* from Toulon.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] HMS *Topaze* attacked these frigates as they arrived, but they were able to reach Corfu before sailing north to augment French defences in the Adriatic.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Throughout the year British attacks intensified, driven by Hoste's *Amphion* operating from Lissa.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Raids on the Italian coastline seized dozens of coastal merchant vessels and gunboats while parties of marines and sailors landed at coastal towns, driving off the defenders and blowing up the fortifications before returning to their ships.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] These successes in the face of negligible French opposition encouraged the British commander in the Mediterranean, Admiral Cuthbert Collingwood, to detail a force specifically to eliminate the French garrisons on the Ionian Islands.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] This expedition, led at sea by Brigadier-General John Oswald from HMS *Warrior* succeeded in landing on the island of Cefalonia on 1 October and forcing the Neapolitan garrison to surrender within hours.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Within days the neighbouring islands of Zante and Ithaca had also surrendered and the detached frigate HMS *Spartan* under Jahleel Brenton effected a successful invasion of Cerigo shortly afterwards.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] These islands were defended by small garrisons, with a few dozen regular French soldiers and larger numbers of men of the Albanian Regiment(400 on Zante, 145 on Cefalonia, 46 on Ithaca, and 27 on Cerigo) on each island.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] These forces were completely inadequate to offer anything but a token resistance; the captured men were transferred to Italy as prisoners of war, but more than a few of the Albanian Regiment's men simply scattered into the countryside and resumed their traditional guerrilla habits.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Most of these escapees, as well as those taken prisoner, were soon induced to enter British service in what eventually became the 1st Regiment Greek Light Infantry.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Over 70% of the Albanian Regiment's men on the four islands switched to the British, including most of the officers.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The 1st Regiment Greek Light Infantry, initially under Richard Church and later under Robert Oswald (brother of John), soon attracted many Greek military leaders who would later play a crucial role in the Greek War of Independence, most notably Theodoros Kolokotronis.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Troop withdrawals late in 1809 delayed any further invasions until March 1810, when Collingwood's temporary successor Thomas Byam Martin detached a squadron of the Mediterranean Fleet for an operation against Santa Maura.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Landings were effected on 22 March, and the island surrendered on 16 April after an eight-day siege of the principal fortress, the attackers considerably aided by the desertion of the garrison's native Greek troops to the Greek volunteers fighting on the British side.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Along with a 2nd Regiment raised in 1813, the Greek units took part in the capture of Paxoi and Parga and the Allied capture of Genoa in 1814.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The conclusion of the War of the Fifth Coalition in late 1809 had changed the political situation in the Adriatic, confirming French possession of the Illyrian Provinces and removing any threat to the Adriatic seaports from Austrian-held territory.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] It also freed the French Army to operate against the Ottoman Empire, as intended in the Treaty of Tilsit.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] It did not however affect the British frigates raiding in the Adriatic under the command of William Hoste, who was now launching coordinated raids against coastal convoys, towns and forts along the Italian coast.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] In the late summer of 1810 the French Navy made their first serious effort to contest British operations in the Adriatic, with the despatch of Bernard Dubourdieu from Toulon in *Favorite*.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Dubourdieu was considered one of the more successful frigate commanders in the French Navy, and he collected the French and Italian forces scattered across the Adriatic into a squadron that significantly outnumbered Hoste's forces.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Hoste was aware of Dubourdieu's movements and maintained a careful watch on the French-led squadron in its base at Ancona.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] In early October, having failed to draw Dubourdieu into battle the previous month, Hoste resupplied at Lissa and returned to the blockade of Ancona, now accompanied by HMS *Cerberus*.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Discovering Dubourdieu and his squadron missing, Hoste gave chase in the direction of Corfu, acting on inaccurate information supplied by a passing Sicilian privateer.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] As Dubourdieu had planned, this detour opened Lissa to attack.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Landing on the island with overwhelming force on 21 October, the French seized the shipping in the harbour but were unable to find the island's garrison, which had retreated to the mountains.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Dubourdieu remained on Lissa for seven hours, but withdrew to Ancona when local fishermen informed him that Hoste was returning from the south.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] To defend against a repeat of this raid and to guard against intervention by the French ship of the line *Rivoli*, which was completing at Venice, the British Mediterranean Fleet sent the third-rate HMS *Montagu* to Lissa.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The arrival of such a powerful vessel stifled any further French initiatives during the year, allowing Hoste to conduct limited raids on the Italian coastline.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] In early 1811 *Montagu* left the Adriatic.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] With HMS *Cerberus* and HMS *Active* detached on operations against the ports of Pescara and Ortona in February, Dubourdieu organised a second attack on Lissa, this time with the ambition of permanently seizing the island and garrisoning it with Italian troops.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Departing Ancona on 11 March with six frigates, numerous support craft and over 500 soldiers, the Franco-Italian squadron sailed for Lissa overnight.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Early in the morning on 12 March, the French were spotted by British observers on Lissa and Hoste brought his squadron, including the recently returned *Cerberus* and *Active*, to meet Dubourdieu off the island's northern coast.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Maintaining a close line of battle, Hoste forced Dubourdieu to attack him directly, Dubourdieu attempting to personally board Hoste's *Amphion* at the head of the Italian soldiers carried aboard his flagship.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Hoste responded to the attempt with fire at point blank range from a carronade containing over 750 musket balls.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The first shot killed Dubourdieu and almost all of his officers, creating confusion in the French squadron that resulted in *Favorite* being wrecked on Lissa's coastline.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Hoste then engaged the following *Flore* and *Bellone*, forcing them both to surrender.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The head of the British line, led by HMS *Volage* engaged the three remaining French and Italian ships, driving off *Danaé* and *Carolina* and capturing *Corona*.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] *Flore* too later escaped to the safety of French batteries off Lesina.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The victory at the Battle of Lissa confirmed British dominance in the region for the next three years, the French unable to replace the losses in ships and experienced officers inflicted at the action.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Attempts to reinforce the Adriatic and maintain the convoys that supplied Corfu were launched from Toulon during the spring of 1811, but few reached the Adriatic; stopped by the British blockade of the Southern French ports.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Of those that escaped the blockade of Toulon, most were subsequently captured by the squadron at Lissa, which had been augmented by the return of HMS *Belle Poule* and the newly arrived HMS *Alceste*, replacing HMS *Amphion* and the wounded Hoste who had returned to Britain.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The squadron also continued the raids on coastal shipping and towns that defined the British campaign, attacking Parenzo and Ragosniza to destroy supply ships sheltering in the harbours.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] In November HMS *Eagle* chased and captured the small French frigate *Corcyre* in a failed attempt by a French convoy to transport supplies to Corfu.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] A day later, the action of 29 November 1811 foiled the most significant French attempt to bring more forces to the Adriatic in 1811 when a British squadron under Captain Murray Maxwell in *Alceste* chased and engaged two frigates and an armed store ship.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] One frigate and the store ship were captured, the other reaching Ancona in a disabled state.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] This action had wide-ranging effects; Napoleon himself took an interest in the reports, and it has been suggested that it was this engagement that convinced him to change the direction of his plans for eastwards expansion from the Balkans to Russia.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] French hopes of regaining supremacy in the Adriatic now rested on the *Rivoli*, a ship of the line under construction at Venice.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Although her completion had been delayed by almost two years, British intelligence was aware of her condition and had periodically supplied ships of the line to observe her movements and engage her if the opportunity should arise.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] In February 1812, *Rivoli* departed Venice for the first time, destined for Pola on her maiden voyage.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Waiting for *Rivoli* was the British HMS *Victorious*, commanded by John Talbot, who chased *Rivoli* and captured her in a four-hour battle in which both sides suffered heavy casualties.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The loss of *Rivoli* ended French efforts to contest British dominance of the Adriatic.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Although the campaign in the theatre would continue until 1814, from February 1812 British raiders were able to attack French convoys, forts, islands and even significant cities with impunity.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] In the summer of 1812, William Hoste returned to the Adriatic as captain of HMS *Bacchante* and raided the Apulian coast for several months.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The freedom with which British cruisers could operate within the Adriatic attracted reinforcements from the Mediterranean Fleet, such as HMS *Eagle* which arrived off Ancona in September and blockaded the city, chasing and destroying whole coastal convoys unopposed.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Even without British intervention, French losses in the Adriatic mounted.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] In November 1811 the *Flore*, veteran of Lissa, was wrecked off Chioggia while in September 1812, the *Danaé* suddenly exploded with heavy loss of life at Trieste.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] For the French Navy, these losses were irreplaceable; French frigates were increasingly unable to escape the blockades of their home ports to reach the Adriatic and ensure the protection of their convoys.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] In early 1813 the first significant British squadron was detached to the Adriatic, under the command of Admiral Thomas Fremantle.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] This force had wide-ranging orders to seize or destroy all French islands, forts and outposts, disrupt coastal trade wherever possible and assist the allied armies of the Sixth Coalition.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Under Fremantle's orders the islands or coastal towns of Lagosta, Curzola, Carlopago, Cherso, Dignano, Giuppana and others were systematically invaded, to be either held by British forces or have their shore facilities slighted to prevent their use by the French.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Fremantle also despatched several officers, including Hoste, to operate independently.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Hoste in *Bacchante* returned to Apulia and attacked a string of ports, castles and anchorages, while Captain George Cadogan in HMS *Havannah* effectively halted the movement of supplies along the northern Italian coast in support of the approaching Austrian armies.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] In June, Fremantle himself led his whole squadron against the important port city of Fiume, seizing or burning 90 vessels from the harbour and huge quantities of naval stores after a sharp battle in the city streets.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Three months later, Fremantle attacked the city of Trieste, blockading it from the sea, bombarding its defences and landing marines and cannon to join with the besieging Austrian armies and force the city's surrender.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] In the autumn of 1813, British raiders enjoyed unopposed domination over the Adriatic sea.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Working in conjunction with the Austrian armies now invading the Illyrian Provinces and Northern Italy, Fremantle's ships were able to rapidly transport British and Austrian troops from one point to another, forcing the surrender of the strategic port of Zara in December.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Cattaro was captured in collaboration with Montenegrin ground troops, and the same result occurred at Ragusa in January 1814.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] By 16 February 1814, Fremantle wrote to his superior Sir Edward Pellew that every French harbour had been captured by British or Austrian troops.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Over 700 French merchant ships had been seized and the only remaining French outpost in the region was Corfu.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The last surviving French warship in the region, the frigate *Uranie*, was destroyed by its own crew at Brindisi on 3 February to prevent her falling into British hands.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The abdication of Napoleon in early April 1814 brought the War of the Sixth Coalition to a close.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Corfu, the longest-held French territory in the Adriatic surrendered and was added to the United States of the Ionian Islands under British protection.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Many awards were presented in Britain for service in the Adriatic, Hoste, Maxwell and Fremantle among those knighted in the 1815 reforms to the knightly orders, as well as the recipients of a large amount of prize money for their captures in the theatre.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The dearth of significant fleet actions in the last nine years of the war also increased public interest in actions such as that at Lissa, which were widely celebrated both before and after the peace.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] Although a minor theatre of the Napoleonic Wars, the naval campaign in the Adriatic may have had far reaching consequences for the wider conflict.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] In particular, the events of 1811 were studied closely by Napoleon; in a chance meeting with Murray Maxwell in 1817, the former Emperor recalled Maxwell's action on 29 November 1811 intimately and commended Maxwell on his victory.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The agreement between France and Russia to support each other in operations against the Ottoman Empire could not have been fulfilled without secure supply lines from France to the Balkans and those supply lines could not be assured without naval control of the Adriatic.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] British historian James Henderson has linked the action of November 1811 to this strategic problem, suggesting that the loss of the convoy and its 200 cannon may have been a factor in Napoleon's decision to change the emphasis of his planned campaign of 1812 from the Balkans to Russia.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] On a smaller scale, the Adriatic was one of the few areas in which French and British ships saw regular combat during the period, *Rivoli* being the last French ship of the line captured in battle at sea.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] The drain of resources from the French Mediterranean Fleet to the Adriatic in the final years of the Napoleonic Wars, prompted by the need to convoy supplies to the isolated garrison of Corfu, frustrated successive French admirals, particularly after the death of Dubourdieu in 1811.
[src:battle-of-navarino/adriatic-campaign-of-1807-1814] In the final months of the war, the ability of the Royal Navy to strike at any point on the coast without opposition undermined the entire defensive structure of the French forces in the region and eased the capture of several heavily defended port cities by the advancing Austrian armies.
[src:battle-of-navarino/al-hasa-expedition-1871] The **Al-Hasa Expedition** was an Ottoman military campaign to annex the Al-Hasa region of eastern Arabia.
[src:battle-of-navarino/al-hasa-expedition-1871] Ostensibly launched to assist Imam Abdullah bin Faisal in reclaiming control over Najd from his brother Saud bin Faisal, the underlying motive was Medhat Pasha's ambition to extend Ottoman dominion over the Persian Gulf.
[src:battle-of-navarino/al-hasa-expedition-1871] Several months into his reign, on March 29, 1871, Imam Abdullah bin Faisal dispatched his envoy Abdul Aziz bin Suwailem to Medhat Pasha, the Ottoman governor of Baghdad, seeking assistance in the conflict against his brother Saud bin Faisal.
[src:battle-of-navarino/al-hasa-expedition-1871] Saud controlled the regions of Al-Ahsa and Qatif, territories that had been wrested from Imam Abdullah bin Faisal.
[src:battle-of-navarino/al-hasa-expedition-1871] The campaign departed Basra on April 20, comprising five infantry columns, a cavalry division and artillery units under the command of Lieutenant General Naser Pasha.
[src:battle-of-navarino/al-hasa-expedition-1871] Accompanying the force was the Sheikh of Al-Muntafiq, leading approximately 1,000 volunteer horsemen from his tribe.
[src:battle-of-navarino/al-hasa-expedition-1871] Additional men from various other Iraqi tribes convened in the town of Az Zubayr.
[src:battle-of-navarino/al-hasa-expedition-1871] Muhammad Saeed Effendi, son of the captain of supervision in Basra, also joined the commander in the expedition.
[src:battle-of-navarino/al-hasa-expedition-1871] A naval contingent from Kuwait joined the campaign, provided by the ruler of Kuwait, Sheikh Abdullah II Al-Sabah, who personally led a fleet of eighty ships.
[src:battle-of-navarino/al-hasa-expedition-1871] The fleet arrived at Ras Tanura on May 13, 1871, coinciding with the Ottoman infantry's land march towards Al-Ahsa.
[src:battle-of-navarino/al-hasa-expedition-1871] From Ras Tanura, the forces progressed towards Qatif, engaging in fierce battles with Saud bin Faisal's supporters, resulting in Qatif's capture on June 3, 1871.
[src:battle-of-navarino/al-hasa-expedition-1871] Subsequently, the campaign advanced to Dammam then to Hofuf.
[src:battle-of-navarino/al-hasa-expedition-1871] Following the Ottoman conquest of Al-Ahsa, Midhat Pasha reneged on his commitment to Imam Abdullah bin Faisal, and the province of Al-Ahsa was separated from the second Saudi state.
[src:battle-of-navarino/al-hasa-expedition-1871] Al Hasa was reincorporated into the Ottoman Empire and became known as the Najd Sanjak.
[src:battle-of-navarino/al-hasa-expedition-1871] For his significant contributions to the campaign, Sheikh Abdullah II Al-Sabah the ruler of Kuwait was bestowed the honorific title of Kaymakam by the Ottoman authorities.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The **Battle of Navarino** was a naval battle fought on 20 October (O.S.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] 8 October) 1827, during the Greek War of Independence (1821–1829), in Navarino Bay (modern Pylos), on the west coast of the Peloponnese peninsula, in the Ionian Sea.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Allied forces from Britain, France, and Russia decisively defeated Ottoman and Egyptian forces which were trying to suppress the Greeks, thereby making Greek independence much more likely.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] An Ottoman armada which, in addition to Imperial warships, included squadrons from the *eyalets* of Egypt and Regency of Algiers and Tunis, was destroyed by an Allied force of British, French and Russian warships.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] It was the last major naval battle in history to be fought entirely with sailing ships, although most ships fought at anchor.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Allies' victory was achieved through superior firepower and gunnery.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The context of the three Great Powers' intervention in the Greek conflict was the Russian Empire's long-running expansion at the expense of the decaying Ottoman Empire.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Russia's ambitions in the region were seen as a major geostrategic threat by the other European powers, which feared the disintegration of the Ottoman Empire and the establishment of Russian hegemony in the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The precipitating factor was support of elements in Orthodox Russia for Greek coreligionists, despite the opposition of Tsar Alexander in 1821 following the Greek rebellion against their Ottoman overlords.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Similarly, despite official British interest in maintaining the Ottoman Empire, British public opinion strongly supported the Greeks.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Fearing unilateral Russian action, Britain and France bound Russia, by treaty, to a joint intervention which aimed to secure Greek autonomy, whilst still preserving Ottoman territorial integrity as a check on Russia.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Powers agreed, by the Treaty of London (1827), to force the Ottoman government to grant the Greeks autonomy within the empire and despatched naval squadrons to the Eastern Mediterranean to enforce their policy.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The naval battle happened more by accident than by design as a result of a manoeuvre by the Allied commander-in-chief, Admiral Edward Codrington, aimed at coercing the Ottoman commander to obey Allied instructions.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The sinking of the Ottomans' Mediterranean fleet saved the fledgling Greek Republic from collapse.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] But it required two more military interventions, by Russia in the form of the Russo-Turkish War of 1828–29 and a French expeditionary force to the Peloponnese to force the withdrawal of Ottoman forces from central and southern Greece, to finally secure Greek independence.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Ottoman Turks had conquered the Greek-controlled Byzantine Empire during the 15th century, taking over its territory and its capital, Constantinople, and becoming its effective successor-state.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In 1821, Greek nationalists revolted against the Ottomans, aiming to liberate ethnic Greeks from four centuries of Ottoman rule.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Fighting raged for several years but by 1825, a stalemate had developed, with the Greeks unable to drive the Ottomans out of most of Greece, but the Ottomans were unable to crush the revolt definitively.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] However, in 1825, the Sultan succeeded in breaking the stalemate.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] He persuaded his powerful *wali* (viceroy) of Egypt, Muhammad Ali Pasha, who was technically his vassal but in practice autonomous, to deploy his Western-trained and equipped army and navy against the Greeks.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In return, the Sultan promised to grant the rebel heartland, the Peloponnese, as a hereditary fief to Ali's eldest son, Ibrahim.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In February 1825, Ibrahim led an expeditionary force of 16,000 into the Peloponnese, and soon overran its western part; he failed, however, to take the eastern section, where the rebel government was based (at Nafplion).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Greek revolutionaries remained defiant, and appointed experienced philhellenic British officers at the head of the army and fleet: Maj Sir Richard Church (land) and Lord Cochrane (sea).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] By this time however, the Greek provisional government's land and sea forces were far inferior to those of the Ottomans and Egyptians: in 1827, Greek regular troops numbered less than 5,000, compared to 25,000 Ottomans in central Greece and 15,000 Egyptians in the Peloponnese.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Also, the Greek government was virtually bankrupt.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Many of the key fortresses on what little territory it controlled were in Ottoman hands.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] It seemed only a matter of time before the Greeks were forced to capitulate.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] At this critical juncture, the Greek cause was rescued by the decision of three Great Powers—Great Britain, France and Russia—to intervene jointly in the conflict.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] From the inception of the Greek revolt until 1826, Anglo-Austrian diplomatic efforts were aimed at ensuring the non-intervention of the other great powers in the conflict.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Their objective was to stall Russian military intervention in support of the Greeks, in order to give the Ottomans time to defeat the rebellion.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] However, the Ottomans proved unable to suppress the revolt during the long period of non-intervention secured by Anglo-Austrian diplomacy.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] By the time the Ottomans were making serious progress, the situation evolved in ways that would make non-interventionism untenable.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In December 1825, the diplomatic landscape changed with the death of Tsar Alexander and the succession of his younger brother Nicholas I to the Russian throne.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Nicholas was a more decisive and risk-taking character than his brother, as well as being far more nationalistic.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The British government's response to the evolving situation was to move towards joint intervention instead of limiting Russian expansionism.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Britain, France, and Russia signed the Treaty of London on 6 July 1827.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The treaty called for an immediate armistice between the belligerents, in effect demanding a cessation of Ottoman military operations in Greece just when the Ottomans had victory in their grasp.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] It also offered Allied mediation in the negotiations on a final settlement that were to follow the armistice.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The treaty called on the Ottomans to grant Greece a degree of autonomy, but envisaged it ultimately remaining under Ottoman suzerainty.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The same clause authorized the signatories in concert to instruct their naval commanders in the Mediterranean to "take all measures that circumstances may suggest" (i.e. including military action) to enforce the Allied demands, if the Ottomans failed to comply within the specified time limit.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] However, the clause added that Allied commanders should not take sides in the conflict.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] On 20 August 1827, the British naval commander-in-chief in the Mediterranean, Vice-Admiral of the Blue Sir Edward Codrington, a veteran of 44 years at sea and a popular hero for his role in the Battle of Trafalgar, received his government's instructions regarding enforcement of the treaty.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Codrington could not have been a less suitable person for a task which required great tact.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] An impetuous fighting sailor, he entirely lacked diplomatic finesse, a quality he despised and derisively ascribed to his French counterpart, Henri de Rigny.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] He was also a sympathiser with the Greek cause, having subscribed to the London Philhellenic Committee.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Exact figures for the Ottoman/Egyptian fleet are difficult to establish.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The figures given above are mainly those enclosed by Codrington in his report.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] These were obtained by one of his officers from the French secretary of the Ottoman fleet, a M.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] However, another report by Letellier to the British ambassador to the Ottomans gives two more frigates and 20 fewer corvettes/brigs for a total of 60 warships.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] James assesses the Ottomans' "effective" strength as even lower: three ships of the line, 15 large frigates and 18 corvettes, totaling just 36 ships.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Flagship of the British squadron, flagship of the Allied fleet.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] distinguished himself during the battle.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] 8 single-deck frigates, 30 corvettes, 5 schooners, 28 brigs, and 5–6 fireships.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The corvettes and brigs carried 1,134 guns.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] James *Naval History of Great Britain* (London, 1837) Vol.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] 476–489 and the French *Revue maritime et coloniale de 1883*.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Vice-Admiral Codrington's instructions were to impose and enforce an armistice on both sides and to interdict the flow of reinforcements and supplies from Asia Minor and Egypt to Ottoman forces in Greece.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] He was to use force only as a last resort.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] On 29 August, the Ottomans formally rejected the Treaty of London's stipulations, triggering the dispatch of Allied representatives to Nafplion.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] On 2 September, the Greek provisional government accepted the armistice.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] This freed Codrington to concentrate on coercing the Ottoman side.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Navarino Bay is a large natural harbour on the west coast of Messinia in the south-west Peloponnese.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] It is approximately 5 km long (between the headlands) and 3 km wide.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The bay is sheltered from the open sea by a long, narrow islet, Sphacteria.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] This islet leaves two entrances to the bay.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Because of a sandbank, the northern one is very narrow and shallow, 100 m wide and just 1 m deep in places, impassable to large boats.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The southern one is much wider, 1,500 m, with an effective passage of 1,000 m width because of rocks.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The southern entrance was at that time guarded by the Ottoman-held New Navarino fortress (Pylos).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] During the Greek insurgency, the bay was used by the Ottoman navy as its main operational base in the Peloponnese.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] A large Ottoman–Egyptian fleet, which had been warned by the British and French to stay away from Greece, left Alexandria on 5 August 1827 and joined other Ottoman units at Navarino on 8 September.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In response, Codrington arrived with his squadron off Navarino on 12 September.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In talks on 25 September with Ibrahim Pasha and the Ottoman admiral, he extracted no explicit verbal promises that they would cease offensive operation.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] However, Codrington did get the pasha to commit a ceasefire until further instructions from the sultan were given.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] After these talks, Codrington withdrew to the nearby British-controlled Ionian island of Zante (Zakynthos), leaving a frigate off Navarino to keep watch on the Ottoman fleet.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] But the Ottomans soon violated these understandings.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Ibrahim was outraged that, while he was expected to observe a ceasefire, Codrington seemingly allowed the Greeks to continue military operations on his vessels unhindered.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Greeks' British commanders were on the offensive at the entrance of the strategically vital Gulf of Corinth.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Church's army laid siege to the Ottoman-held port of Patras, while Cochrane organised a revolt behind Ottoman lines in Epirus.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] By sea, Frank Abney Hastings, a former British naval officer now serving with the Greeks, used a steam-powered warship, the *Karteria*, to launch a daring night raid on 29/30 September at Itea on the northern shore of the gulf, sinking nine Ottoman gunboats.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The problem for Codrington was that these officers were acting on their own initiative, largely ignoring the often contradictory directives of their employer, the Greek provisional government.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Recognising that appeals to the latter were ineffective, Codrington despatched aides directly to the British commanders to demand that they cease operations, but with little result.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] After a vain protest to Codrington, Ibrahim decided to act.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] On 1 October, he despatched a naval squadron to reinforce the Patras garrison.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] It was intercepted by Codrington's squadron at the entrance to the gulf, and forced to return to Navarino, shadowed by Codrington.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Ibrahim tried again on the night of 3/4 October, this time leading the squadron in person.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Using the darkness, he succeeded in slipping past the British picket ship unobserved, but was prevented from entering the gulf by a strong headwind.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] His squadron was obliged to anchor in the lee of Cape Pappas and wait out the storm.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] This gave Codrington time to catch up, and the British squadron, after a whole day of fighting the wind, arrived off Pappas on the evening of 4 October.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Codrington fired a series of warning broadsides, and Ibrahim reluctantly decided to turn back.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In the meantime, Ibrahim's scorched-earth policy continued unabated on land.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The fires of burning villages and fields were clearly visible from Allied ships standing offshore.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] A British landing party reported that the population of Messinia was close to mass starvation.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] On 13 October, Codrington was joined off Navarino by a French squadron under Rigny and a Russian squadron under L. van Heiden.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] On 18 October, after futile attempts to contact Ibrahim Pasha, Codrington, in conference with his Allied colleagues, took the fateful decision to enter Navarino Bay and anchor his ships face-to-face with the Ottoman/Egyptian fleet.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] It was decided that with winter approaching, it was impracticable to maintain an effective blockade of Navarino, and that in any event, the population of the Peloponnese had to be safeguarded.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Although this was a highly provocative act, Codrington claimed that there was no intention to engage in battle, but only to make a show of force to induce the Ottomans to respect the armistice and to desist from atrocities against the civilian population.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Allied navies at this time were still deploying essentially the same technology as during the Napoleonic Wars: sailing ships, unarmoured wooden hulls and muzzle-loading smoothbore cannon.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The navies, especially the British one, had ignored the new technologies that were to transform them by the 1850s: steam propulsion, ironclad hulls, rifled guns and explosive shells.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] All these had been invented by 1827, but their development for naval warfare, let alone introduction, met dogged resistance from senior naval echelons.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] However, the Royal Navy's warships had seen some improvements.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Ships with triple gun-decks such as Nelson's famous HMS *Victory* had been phased out.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Triple-deckers had been found to be too unstable and difficult to manoeuvre.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The standard *Canopus*-class was a double-deck 74–84 ship of the line, based on the successful "74" French design.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In addition, gun-calibres had been upgraded.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Napoleonic-era *Fame*-class had been equipped with 32-pounders on the main gun-deck, 18-pounders on the upper deck and 9- and 12-pounders on the super-structures (quarterdeck and forecastle).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In contrast, the guns were now all 24- or 32-pounders (plus a couple of massive 68-pounder carronades on the super-structures).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Frigates were either double-deckers of 50–60 guns (known as large frigates) or single-deckers with 24–44 guns.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Most of the Allied ships, however, were still veteran Napoleonic-era warhorses (e.g.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Codrington's only *Canopus*-class was his flagship, HMS *Asia* (launched 1824), although *Genoa* (an impounded French "74") was also post-Napoleonic (1816).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In the French squadron, Rigny was so appalled by the state of the three ships of the line sent to him that he decided to keep his flag on the *Sirène*, a modern frigate.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Overall at Navarino, the Allies had 22 ships and 1,258 guns against the Ottomans' 78 ships with 2,180 guns (figures exclude smaller boats and fireships).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] But the numbers masked major Allied advantages in ship-types, gun-calibres and crew quality.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] As a result of these, Allied gun-crews could fire more powerful, more frequent and more accurate cannonades than their Ottoman counterparts.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Allies had a substantial superiority in front-line combat vessels: 10 ships of the line to the Ottomans' three.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] This advantage was only partially offset by the Ottomans' seven double-deck frigates against one Allied vessel of this kind.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The great majority of the Ottoman–Egyptian fleet were smaller vessels – 58 corvettes and brigs – which were of little use against the Allied heavyweights: they had much smaller firepower, and, their decks being lower, could easily be dismasted by raking fire.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In addition, the Ottoman–Egyptians mainly deployed smaller-calibre guns than the Allies (often the guns discarded by the Allies when they upgraded their own calibres).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Most of the Allied crews had gained extensive combat experience in the Napoleonic Wars, which had only ended 12 years previously, and were service professionals.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In contrast, the Ottoman crews only had combat experience against the Greek revolutionary naval forces, which although gallant and effective, bore no resemblance to the navies of the Great Powers.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In many cases, Ottoman crews practiced impressment to fill their ships' complements.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Some Ottoman crew were even found, after the battle, to have been shackled at their posts (convicts, Greek prisoners or other involuntary recruits).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Egyptian contingent, the largest and best-equipped of the Ottoman fleet at Navarino, had been trained by a team of French officers, under the overall direction of Capt J-M.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] These officers acted as "shadow-captains" of the large Egyptian vessels, each advising the nominal Egyptian captain.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The day before the battle, Rigny persuaded these officers to withdraw from the Egyptian fleet so as to avoid the possibility of fighting against their own navy (they moved to an Austrian brig that was in the bay, ostensibly neutral but in reality providing logistical support for Ottoman operations).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Letellier himself was sick and also took no part.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] This deprived the Egyptians of experienced command.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] For the Allies, probably the Ottomans' most dangerous weapon were their fireships.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] These had long been deployed to devastating effect by the Greek revolutionaries against the Ottomans, who had learnt how to use them through hard experience.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Fireships were posted on the wings of the Ottoman formation, and could, if effectively deployed, wreak mayhem on Allied boats concentrated in enclosed waters, especially as Allied sailors had no experience of this kind of warfare.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The danger was graphically demonstrated in the early phase of the battle, when the French ship of the line *Scipion* narrowly escaped being destroyed by a fireship.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Ottomans possessed a shore battery on each side of the main entrance to the bay, in Navarino fort and on the southern tip of Sphacteria island.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] These could have seriously impeded Allied entry into the bay, but Codrington was clearly confident that the Ottomans would not start a shooting war.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Following an elaborate defensive plan proposed by Letellier, the Ottoman-Egyptian fleet was anchored in a horseshoe formation, in three lines, extending from Navarino fort to the southern tip of Sphacteria island, where the Ottoman shore battery lay.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The front line consisted of the ships of the line and large frigates; the second line contained the remaining frigates and larger corvettes; the third consisted of the remaining smaller vessels.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The idea was that the smaller vessels could fire through the gaps in the frontline, whilst being protected by the larger ships from Allied attack.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] On the ends of the horseshoe were stationed corvettes and fireships.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The latter could be towed by boats into position covered by the smaller corvettes and shore batteries.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Allied plan was to anchor in the free water inside the crescent.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Codrington's squadron would take up position facing the centre of the Ottoman line; the French and Russian squadrons would face the Ottoman left and right wings respectively.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The French position in the line had been specifically determined so that they would face the Egyptian fleet, which had been trained by the French and might be reluctant to fight against Egypt's closest European ally.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In conventional naval doctrine, Codrington's plan would have been regarded as an unacceptable risk, as it would have invited the enemy to try to surround the Allies.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Furthermore, with the prevailing wind blowing from the SW, straight up the entrance, Codrington risked becoming trapped, unable to extricate his squadrons quickly if necessary.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The adoption of this high-risk plan shows the total confidence of the Allied commanders in the tactical superiority of their vessels.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] At 1.30 p.m., on 20 October 1827, off the entrance to Navarino Bay, Codrington signalled to the Allied fleet: "PREPARE FOR ACTION" and Allied crews were ordered to stand to their guns.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Gun-ports were left half-open, but Allied captains were under strict orders to open fire only if attacked.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] At 2.00 p.m., Allied warships, with Codrington in the lead in *Asia*, began filing into the bay through the southern entrance, proceeding in two lines, British followed by French to starboard (SE, closest to Navarino) and Russians to port abreast but slightly behind the French.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] There was no attempt to prevent their entry by the Ottoman shore batteries or their corvettes posted at the entrance, but Codrington received a launch carrying a message from Ibrahim Pasha.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] This stated that he had not given permission for the Allies to enter the bay, and demanded that they withdraw.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Codrington dismissed Ibrahim's objection, replying that he had come to give orders, not to take them.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] He warned that if the Ottomans opened fire, their fleet would be destroyed.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] As his flagship dropped anchor in the middle of the Ottoman line, Codrington ordered a brass band to play on deck to emphasize his peaceful intentions.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] By 2.15 p.m., the three British ships of the line had dropped anchor in their allotted positions.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Meanwhile, as the Allied vessels moved into position, along the Ottoman lines trumpets sounded action stations.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Ottoman crews scrambled to meet the unexpected intrusion into their base.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] At this point, at the entrance, fighting broke out.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Codrington claimed that hostilities were started by the Ottomans.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] At the entrance to the bay, Capt Thomas Fellowes on the frigate *Dartmouth* had been detailed, with six smaller vessels (2 brigs and 4 schooners) to keep watch on the group of Ottoman corvettes and fireships on the left flank of the Ottoman line.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] As the Allied ships continued moving into the bay, Fellowes noticed that an Ottoman crew was preparing a fireship and sent a boat to instruct them to desist.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Ottomans fired on the boat and lighted the fireship.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Fellowes sent a cutter to tow the fireship to a safe distance, but the Ottomans fired on the cutter, inflicting casualties.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Fellowes opened musket fire on the fireship crew to cover his men.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] At this point the French flagship *Sirène*, which was just then entering the bay on the tail of the British-French line, opened fire with muskets to support *Dartmouth*.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] An Ottoman corvette then attacked *Sirène* with its guns.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] This chain reaction spread along the line, so that within a short time, there was general engagement.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The battle thus began before the Allies could complete their deployment.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In fact, this proved to be a tactical advantage, as it meant some Allied ships were not yet at anchor and could therefore manoeuvre more swiftly.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Nevertheless, most ships fought at anchor.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] There was naturally very little scope for manoeuvre, except to change the orientation of the ship by hauling on the springs on the anchor chains.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] With ships blasting each other at very close range, the encounter was mostly a matter of attrition, in which superior Allied firepower and gunnery were critical.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Rigny's *Sirène* fought a lengthy duel with the 64-gun frigate *Ihsania*, which finally blew up.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] *Sirène* suffered significant casualties and damage.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] *Sirène*, with the support of *Trident* and *Scipion*, then bombarded the fort of Navarino and eventually silenced its shore battery.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] *Albion*, which had wrecked an Ottoman frigate as she anchored, was under fire from all three Ottoman ships of the line simultaneously.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Fortunately for her, the enemy gunnery was inept.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Even so, *Breslaw*'s intervention was later acknowledged by the captain of *Albion* as having saved his ship from annihilation.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] *Breslaw* then proceeded to play a leading role in the destruction of Ottoman admiral Tahir Pasha's flagship, the *Ghiuh Rewan* (84), and at least four frigates.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Codrington's *Asia* (84) was anchored between Ottoman admiral Capitan Bey's flagship, *Fahti Bahri* (74), and Egyptian Moharram Bey's frigate *Guerrière* (60).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Capitan Bey opened fire, but Moharram Bey sent word to Codrington that he was not going to attack.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] This enabled *Asia* to concentrate its fire on *Fahti Bahri*, which was in a poor condition and inadequately manned.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] *Asia*'s deadly fire shortly disabled her.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Codrington then sent an interpreter, a Greek, P.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Mikelis, to parley with Moharram Bey; but Mikelis was shot dead as he went aboard.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] *Guerrière* then opened fire, but was reduced to a burning wreck within 20 minutes by crushing broadsides from *Asia* and *Azov*.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] However, *Asia* suffered severe casualties and damage due to a concentration of heavy fire from smaller Ottoman boats in the second and third lines of the Ottoman formation: as Letellier had planned, these boats fired through the gaps in the front line.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Codrington also believed that *Asia* had taken serious hits by mistake from sister *Genoa*.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Russians under Van Heiden were the last to take up station, as was planned.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Their position, on the right end of the Ottoman crescent, was the most exposed.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The fighting in this sector was even more intense than elsewhere.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] *Azov* sank or disabled three large frigates and a corvette, but herself took 153 hits, several below the waterline.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The British frigates *Armide* and *Talbot* initially had to face the frigates on the Ottoman right wing and the island shore battery unsupported, as the other two frigates were away and arrived later.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] They were saved from annihilation by the arrival of the Russian frigates.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The smaller British and French vessels (brigs and the schooners *Alcyone* and *Daphné*), under the overall direction of frigate *Dartmouth*, had been allotted the vital task of preventing fireship attacks.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Their success was complete: apart from the initial fireship attack on *Scipion*, not a single fireship struck a target during the battle.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] A number of the smaller vessels greatly distinguished themselves, suffering casualties as great, in proportion, as the ships of the line.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] By about 4 p.m., all three Ottoman ships of the line and most of the large frigates of the first line had been despatched.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] This left the mass of smaller vessels in the second and third lines at the mercy of the Allied ships of the line, all of which were still operational.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] During the ensuing massacre, Codrington tried twice to order a ceasefire, but his signals were either invisible because of the thick smoke or ignored in the heat of the battle.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Within the following two hours, virtually the entire Ottoman fleet was destroyed, despite the signal bravery of the Ottoman crews, which was praised by Codrington himself in his despatches.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Three quarters were sunk: many of them, dismasted but still afloat and reparable, were blown up or set on fire by their own crews to prevent them falling into Allied hands.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] This contributed to the horrendous Ottoman and Egyptian casualty figures, as many men were trapped in burning or exploding vessels.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Some, as mentioned, were shackled to their posts.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Ottoman casualties given to Codrington by Letellier were approx.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] 3,000 killed, 1,109 wounded, although Codrington claimed the reverse was more likely.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Of the entire Ottoman-Egyptian armada of 78 vessels, just eight remained seaworthy: one dismasted ship of the line, two frigates, and five corvettes.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Allied casualties were given by Codrington as 181 killed, 480 wounded (including Codrington's youngest son, midshipman H.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Codrington, serving on *Asia* under his father, who was badly injured but made a full recovery).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Several Allied ships were severely damaged: the Russian ships *Azov*, *Gangut* and *Iezekiil* were disabled.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The three British ships of the line had to be sent back to the United Kingdom for repairs.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] According to one source, despite the rough handling all the ships of the line had endured and the danger from exploding Ottoman vessels, not a single Allied vessel was sunk.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] As the guns fell silent at dusk in Navarino Bay, news of the outcome raced over the Peloponnese and to the rest of Greece.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In village after village, church bells started a continuous peal in the night.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] People rushed into village squares, to be greeted by the news that the Ottoman Sultan and his hated vassal Ibrahim Pasha no longer possessed a Mediterranean fleet.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In a maritime country like Greece, the implication was evident—the fledgling Greek state was saved.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Wild rejoicing broke out, and lasted through the night and for days after.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Huge bonfires were lit on the mountaintops of the Peloponnese and Mount Parnassos in central Greece.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Celebrations swept even the occupied regions, which the demoralised Ottoman garrisons made little effort to prevent.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Despite the celebrations, the Sultan still disposed of a total of around 40,000 troops in central and southern Greece, entrenched in powerful fortresses.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The final liberation of Greece was still far off, unless the Ottomans could be induced to accept the Treaty of London.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Russia's long-expected declaration of war on the Ottomans occurred in April 1828, starting the 11th Russo-Turkish War (1828–1829).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] A Russian army of 100,000 men swept aside the Ottoman forces in the Romanian Principalities, crossed the Danube, and laid siege to Silistra, Varna and Shumla, the key Ottoman-held fortresses in Rumelia (Bulgaria).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In August 1828, Ali agreed to the withdrawal of his forces from the Peloponnese.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Ibrahim initially refused to comply with his father's evacuation orders, but gave way shortly after the French troops landed in Navarino Bay at the end of August, to a jubilant reception by the Greeks, to begin their Morea expedition.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Egyptians finally left in October 1828, a year after the naval battle.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The French proceeded to clear the remaining Ottoman garrisons in the Peloponnese, which offered only token resistance, by the end of 1828.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In the subsequent months, Greek forces regained control of central Greece in a lightning campaign.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In September 1829, with the Russian army camped just 40 miles from his palace, the Ottoman Sultan was forced to capitulate.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] By the Treaty of Adrianople, he conceded a long list of Russian demands, one of which was acceptance of Greek autonomy as defined in the Treaty of London.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] However, the Sultan's acceptance came too late to save Ottoman sovereignty over Greece.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Buoyed by the Ottoman disasters on land and sea, and their own military successes, the Greeks refused to accept anything less than full independence.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Finally, at the London Protocol of 1830, the Allies dropped their policy of Ottoman suzerainty and accepted Greek independence.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Later that year, the Sultan was forced by the Allied powers to sign the Treaty of Constantinople (1832), formally recognizing the new Kingdom of Greece as an independent state.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] In the aftermath of Navarino, Codrington pressed for an Egyptian withdrawal from the Peloponnese, but it took a year to achieve it.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The news of Navarino made Codrington a hero twice over in the eyes of the general British public.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] But in Whitehall, senior naval and diplomatic echelons were appalled by the outcome of his campaign.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] It was considered that Codrington had grossly exceeded his instructions by provoking a showdown with the Ottoman fleet, and that his actions had gravely compromised the Ottoman ability to resist Russian encroachment.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] At a social event, King George IV was reported as referring to the battle as "this untoward [*i.e.*, undesirable] event".
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Codrington's political situation in London became even more precarious in January 1828, when Wellington became Prime Minister.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The coincident launch of Tsar Nicholas's war on the Ottomans realised the worst fears of British policy-makers and deepened their anger at Codrington.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Initially, official disapproval of Codrington had to be restrained because of the admiral's huge popularity with the public.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Admiralty's revenge took petty form, such as its refusal, despite repeated requests by Codrington, to pay his crews their traditional prize money from the sale of captured Ottoman treasure and goods.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Meanwhile, Wellington was biding his time until he felt it was politically safe to remove Codrington from the Mediterranean theatre.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Finally, in June 1828, the Admiralty announced that Codrington was being relieved of his command (although he remained in acting-command until his replacement arrived in August).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Although the King felt obliged by public opinion to grant Codrington the high honour of the Grand Cross of the Bath, the Admiralty's failure to give him another operational command in his remaining decade of service was eloquent testimony to his fall from favour.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Codrington spent much time in his later years defending his actions in Greece.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] His enemies accused him of deliberately plotting the destruction of the Ottoman fleet because of his Hellenophile sympathies, a charge that Codrington vehemently denied.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The issue turned on whether he knew that his move into Navarino Bay would result in a battle.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] On the one hand, there are Codrington's clear orders to his captains to engage only if attacked.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] On the other, is Codrington's private correspondence, notably to his sister, which suggests that he regarded a military showdown as inevitable.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] There are a number of memorials to the battle around Navarino Bay.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The main square of Pylos, Three Admirals' Square (Greek: Πλατεία Τριών Ναυάρχων), has as its centrepiece a three-sided marble monument, with profiles of Codrington, Van Heiden, and Rigny on the three sides.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Memorials to the dead of the three allies are to be found on the islands in the bay: Helonaki islet (British), Pylos islet (French), and Sphacteria island (Russian).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Russian memorial is the most impressive, consisting of a small wooden chapel in the Russian Orthodox style.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Additionally, there is a memorial to the philhellene Santarosa, who was killed in an earlier battle, on the shore of Sphacteria.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The battle is commemorated each year on 20 October by all-day celebrations in Three Admirals' Square in Pylos, hosted by the Mayor of Pylos.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] The Russian, French and British governments send representatives to the ceremonies, and in the case of the Russians, a warship and its crew.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] It was the source of the name for the Russian corvette *Navarin*, the Russian battleship *Navarin*, and the French ship of the line *Navarin*.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Some bronze from the sunken Ottoman ships was bought by Anton Samassa in Trieste and was in 1834 used for the main bell of St.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] Judoc's Church in Sveti Jošt near Kranj, Carniola (now Slovenia).
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] It bears an inscription by the Slovene Romantic poet France Prešeren: "My bronze was found at the bottom of the sea, when the kingdom of Turkey was ended in Helade by Navarino.
[src:battle-of-navarino/battle-of-navarino] It was bought by a pilgrim; cast into a bell by Samassa, now I announce God's honour from St.
